{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594579"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:50:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:50:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15328"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15328"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.2,0.04,0.12,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8019"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85733"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8019"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70032"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5219"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19487"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85733"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the emergency department following intentional paracetamol overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about paracetamol toxicity is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["N-acetylcysteine replenishes depleted glutathione stores","Toxic metabolites accumulate when glutathione levels rise","Zone 1 hepatocytes are primarily affected","AST levels typically exceed ALT levels","Toxic effects occur only with chronic overdose"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn paracetamol toxicity, the drug is metabolised to N-acetyl-p-benzoquinone imine (NAPQI), a toxic metabolite. \u003Cstrong\u003EN-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E serves as a glutathione precursor, helping to replenish depleted stores and prevent hepatic injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic metabolites accumulate when glutathione levels rise\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - NAPQI accumulates when glutathione stores are depleted, not when they rise. Glutathione normally conjugates with NAPQI to form non-toxic metabolites. When glutathione is exhausted, unconjugated NAPQI builds up and causes cellular damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZone 1 hepatocytes are primarily affected\u003C/strong\u003E - The toxic effects primarily affect zone 3 (centrizonal) hepatocytes due to higher concentrations of cytochrome P450 enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAST levels typically exceed ALT levels\u003C/strong\u003E - In paracetamol toxicity, ALT is typically higher than AST\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic effects occur only with chronic overdose\u003C/strong\u003E - Significant toxicity can occur with a single acute overdose\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Paracetamol toxicity depletes hepatic glutathione stores, leading to accumulation of toxic metabolites.","N-acetylcysteine acts as a glutathione precursor to replenish depleted stores.","Paracetamol hepatotoxicity typically shows ALT elevation greater than AST."],"references":["Chidiac AS, Buckley NA, Noghrehchi F, Cairns R. Paracetamol (acetaminophen) overdose and hepatotoxicity: mechanism, treatment, prevention measures, and estimates of burden 